hints_latex:
Alternatively, try using Taylor series. Recall that the Taylor series
centered at 0 for the function $e^x$ is given by

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}
\end{align*}

sols_latex:
We will use the ratio test to prove that this series is absolutely
convergent. Each term in the series is

\begin{align*}
a_n = \frac{(-2011)^n}{n!}
\end{align*}

and so we have that

\begin{align*}
\frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n} = \frac{\frac{(-2011)^{n+1}}{(n+1)!}}{ \frac{(-2011)^n}{n!}} = \frac{-2011 n!}{(n+1)!} = -\frac{2011}{n+1}
\end{align*}

We see then that $\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n} = 0 < 1$, and so
the series converges absolutely.

As per the second hint, we note that the series is given by

\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(-2011)^n}{n!} = e^{-2011}
\end{align*}

Since the function $e^x$ converges absolutely over the whole real line,
it follows that this series does as well.

